<script>
var excerpt_text_list = {"9780593732434":"Chapter 1<br><br>Ada<br><br>I&rsquo;ve come in contact with a lot of liars, but none quite so big as Google. I&rsquo;m not trying to discredit the search engine, but I am trying to bring attention to its most annoying inaccuracies. In this case, telling me that the dive bar I was sitting in&mdash;&shy;only because it was the only establishment in the small town of Meadowlark, Wyoming, that was open past ten o&rsquo;clock on a Sunday night&mdash;&shy;served food.<br><br>It did not.<br><br>Google&rsquo;s stupid bar-&shy;graph busy-&shy;meter also said that the Devil&rsquo;s Boot&mdash;&shy;not sure if that&rsquo;s actually the name of the bar, considering that there&rsquo;s not a sign anywhere that indicates that&mdash;&shy;wasn&rsquo;t busy.<br><br>It was.<br><br>Not insanely busy, but busy enough to at least get the &ldquo;moderately busy&rdquo; designation on Google.<br><br>There was also a very boisterous cabal of old men at the bar&mdash;&shy;Google couldn&rsquo;t have told me that. But if there&rsquo;d been any pictures of this place on its business page, I probably could&rsquo;ve deduced that for myself.<br><br>And avoided the Devil&rsquo;s Boot altogether.<br><br>Stupid Google.<br><br>This place was exactly what I thought of whenever I pictured a small-&shy;town dive bar. There was old-&shy;school country playing on a jukebox and an excessive number of neon signs; it smelled like stale cigarettes, and there were spots on the floor that my Doc Martens stuck to when I walked.<br><br>I&rsquo;m not a snob. I&rsquo;ve got nothing against a good dive bar. I just didn&rsquo;t think I&rsquo;d end up sitting in one. Not today.<br><br>When I left San Francisco yesterday and started making my way to Wyoming, a dive bar would&rsquo;ve been the last place I wanted to be the night before I started the biggest job of my career.<br><br>But I was hungry, and the small but weirdly quaint motel I was staying in tonight didn&rsquo;t have the best Wi-Fi, so I left in search of sustenance and internet access, but I only found one of those two things. What kind of dive bar has no food but good Wi-Fi?<br><br>The kind with a very tall and very hot bartender who took pity on me when I asked about food and fished out a snack-&shy;size bag of Doritos from behind the bar and gave them to me with my whiskey and Diet Coke. I didn&rsquo;t ask how old they were&mdash;&shy;I didn&rsquo;t want to know&mdash;&shy;but I had a pretty good idea, considering they were almost soft. They tasted like the bag had been open for a while, though it was still sealed when I got it.<br><br>After that, I settled for a high-&shy;top table in the corner. On the wall behind it, there was a neon sign of a cowboy riding a beer bottle like a bull. The ridiculousness of it tugged at the corners of my mouth, and I liked that feeling.<br><br>Honestly, I didn&rsquo;t know if eating the Doritos that could probably qualify for a senior citizens discount was better than eating nothing, but here I was, eating them.<br><br>I dusted the nacho cheese dust off my fingers so it wouldn&rsquo;t dirty my iPad screen. I had pulled up the email threads between Weston Ryder and me, double-checking the time I was supposed to be at Rebel Blue Ranch tomorrow morning and making sure I had the map downloaded to my phone, just in case.<br><br>That was me, Ada Hart, nothing if not prepared.<br><br>I didn&rsquo;t know much about Rebel Blue&mdash;&shy;just what Teddy had told me over the past few months. I knew Teddy from my first year of college. We went to the same school in Colorado&mdash;&shy;at least for my first year. After that, I ended up transferring to be closer to home.<br><br>Going home was now a decision that I deeply regretted, because it had led to what would forever be known as &ldquo;the incident&rdquo; to me, but also known as my wedding to others.<br><br>I shook any thought of that and him out of my head.<br><br>After I left Denver, I stayed in touch with Teddy&mdash;&shy;mostly on socials&mdash;&shy;and I was grateful for that now. She was the one who&rsquo;d referred me to Weston, who I think was the owner of Rebel Blue, but I didn&rsquo;t know for sure. When you google it&mdash;&shy;again, stupid Google&mdash;&shy;you only get the information that it&rsquo;s a cattle ranch and that it&rsquo;s nearly eight thousand acres.<br><br>I guess I could&rsquo;ve asked Teddy, but I didn&rsquo;t want to bug her. She&rsquo;d done enough for me.<br><br>I didn&rsquo;t know how to conceptualize eight thousand acres. F***ing massive is what I was thinking, when I heard one of the old men at the bar giving the bartender a hard time.<br><br>&ldquo;What kind of bar runs out of ice?&rdquo; he growled incredulously.<br><br>&ldquo;The kind that has a bunch of sad old men that drink whiskey like water,&rdquo; the bartender fired back. I looked up at them. The bartender had a small smile on his face, so he couldn&rsquo;t be too upset with the jabs. &ldquo;Gus is bringing some, so make that drink last for the next ten minutes.&rdquo; He pointed at the glass in front of the man, and the man scoffed at him.<br><br>I felt my phone vibrate on the table and picked it up.<br><br>Teddy: Hey! Did you make it okay?<br><br>Me: Yeah&mdash;&shy;just doing some prep before tomorrow.<br><br>Teddy: EXCELLENT.<br><br>Teddy: This is going to be so fun.<br><br>Teddy: I&rsquo;ll stop by this week.<br><br>Teddy: Can&rsquo;t wait for you to shine!<br><br>I saw that I also had a text from my business partner, Evan&mdash;&shy;he was the contractor&mdash;&shy;and my mom, who was no doubt telling me that I was wasting my time in Wyoming.<br><br>Maybe I was, but for some reason, I really didn&rsquo;t think so.<br><br>I slid my phone back onto the table and flipped it facedown. I needed to focus. Over the past four months, I&rsquo;d exchanged hundreds of emails with Weston. We&rsquo;d discussed his vision, we&rsquo;d decided on timelines, crews, and costs. People always thought that tearing down walls was step one, but it was actually like step three hundred. I was going over steps one through two hundred and ninety-&shy;nine when a giant ball of white fluff appeared at my feet.<br><br>&ldquo;Waylon! Goddammit,&rdquo; I heard the bartender yell. I assumed Waylon was the dog sitting at my feet and staring up at me with his tongue hanging out and a crazed look in his eyes.<br><br>What an angel.<br><br>I leaned down and gave him a scratch on his very soft and furry head. Huh, less than a few hours in Meadowlark and this place was pulling smiles out of me at a record-&shy;setting rate.<br><br>&ldquo;Seriously?&rdquo; I heard the bartender whine. &ldquo;Who the hell brings his dog to a bar?&rdquo; I looked up just as a man walked in the door.<br><br>Damn. What the hell were they putting in the water in Meadowlark, Wyoming?<br><br>From here I could see that he wasn&rsquo;t as tall as the bar&shy;tender,&#160;but close. His open flannel shirt covered a white &shy;T-&shy;shirt that clung to his chest. My eyes glided over him until they hit his worn-&shy;out cowboy boots.<br><br>Maybe it was because I&rsquo;d been surrounded by tech bros in Patagonia vests for too long, but this man was doing something for me.<br><br>I bet he had rough hands. Working hands. For a split second, I imagined what they would feel like if he dragged them across my body.<br><br>Nope. No. Definitely not.<br><br>Do not go there.<br><br>We were not about to have fantasies about the mystery cowboy in the dusky dive bar&mdash;&shy;no matter how good-&shy;looking he was.<br><br>I was here to work.<br><br>I got snapped back to reality by my new furry friend licking my hands&mdash;&shy;probably tasting the elderly Dorito dust.<br><br>I couldn&rsquo;t help but listen to the exchange between the bartender and the cowboy. Eavesdropping was one of my favorite hobbies. &ldquo;What kind of bar runs out of ice?&rdquo; the cowboy shot at the bartender. The group of old men whooped in agreement.<br><br>&ldquo;Where&rsquo;s your brother?&rdquo; the bartender asked.<br><br>&ldquo;Busy.&rdquo; The cowboy shrugged his shoulders.<br><br>&ldquo;Where&rsquo;s my ice?&rdquo;<br><br>&ldquo;Truck.&rdquo;<br><br>&ldquo;You couldn&rsquo;t bring it in?&rdquo;<br><br>&ldquo;I figured you could do that part.&rdquo; The bartender shook his head but came out from behind the bar and walked out the door. It was obvious that there was some sort of bond between these two. I didn&rsquo;t think they were brothers&mdash;&shy;they didn&rsquo;t look alike&mdash;&shy;but there was something.<br><br>Not brothers, but definitely bros.<br><br>&ldquo;Get your dog,&rdquo; the bartender said on his way out. &ldquo;Please.&rdquo;<br><br>The cowboy&rsquo;s eyes started scanning the bar&mdash;&shy;probably looking for his dog&mdash;&shy;but landed right on me. Me, whose hand was currently getting a thorough licking, and who was unashamedly and unabashedly staring at the cowboy.<br><br>I should&rsquo;ve looked away, but I didn&rsquo;t.<br><br>I couldn&rsquo;t tell what color his eyes were from here, but I wanted to.<br><br>We stared at each other for way longer than was socially acceptable, and he flashed me a small smile that hinted at a dimple on either side of his face.<br><br>Not f***ing dimples.<br><br>Those should be illegal.<br><br>Or at least require some sort of warning before flashing them at people.<br><br>Warning: Dimples may appear and cause panty-&shy;dropping.<br><br>It looked like he was about to start toward me, but our weird and intense stare-&shy;off was interrupted by the bartender putting an ice cube down the back of the cowboy&rsquo;s shirt.<br \/><span class=\"excrpt_cp\">Excerpted from <span class=\"excrpt_cp_ttl\">Swift and Saddled<\/span> by Lyla Sage.  Copyright &#169; 2024 by Lyla Sage. All rights reserved. No part of this excerpt may be reproduced or reprinted without permission in writing from the publisher.<\/span>","9780593732441